---
// Blog post: Florida and Brevard County painting license changes — what homeowners should know when hiring.
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = 'Florida Painting License Law Change: What Brevard Homeowners Should Know';
const description =
  'Florida ended the state painting license requirement in 2021, and Brevard County local licenses stopped in July 2025. Here\'s what it means for homeowners hiring painters.';

const ogImage = '/images/blog/florida-painting-license-law.jpg';

const vettingItems = [
  {
    heading: 'They can clearly explain their process',
    body: 'Ask: "Can you walk me through how you prepare surfaces before painting?" A good painter should describe pressure washing, mildew treatment, caulking, crack repair, and priming — and explain why these steps are especially important in coastal Florida.',
  },
  {
    heading: 'They carry general liability insurance',
    body: 'Ask to see their certificate of insurance for larger jobs to protect your property in case something goes wrong.',
  },
  {
    heading: 'They provide a written scope of work',
    body: 'Avoid vague agreements. You should receive a clear written outline of what is included.',
  },
  {
    heading: 'They have verifiable local references',
    body: 'Check their Google Business profile or ask for recent references from Brevard County homeowners. Look for feedback that mentions communication, preparation, and follow-through.',
  },
];
---

<Layout {title} {description} {ogImage}>
  <main class="page-container py-12 sm:py-16">
    <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-10 text-base leading-relaxed text-charcoal sm:space-y-12 sm:text-lg">
      <header class="space-y-4">
        <figure class="-mx-4 overflow-hidden rounded-xl sm:mx-0">
          <img
            src={ogImage}
            alt="Scales of justice in front of a well-painted Florida home exterior"
            width={1200}
            height={675}
            class="aspect-[16/9] w-full object-cover"
            loading="eager"
          />
        </figure>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium text-purple">Homeowner Guidance</p>
        <h1 class="font-display text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
          Florida Removed the Painting License Requirement. Here's What That Actually Means.
        </h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-muted sm:text-xl">
          Brevard County Painting Contractor License Changes: What Homeowners Need to Know
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted">
          If Walls Could Talk LLC · Brevard County, FL · Homeowner Guidance
        </p>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-muted">
          <p>
            In 2021, Florida eliminated the state requirement for a painting contractor license. Then in July 2025,
            Brevard County ended its local license requirement for painting as well.
          </p>
          <p>
            Today, there is no state or local license required to offer painting services in Brevard County. This means
            homeowners have more options — but it also makes it even more important to carefully vet the painters you
            hire.
          </p>
          <p>
            The right crew will stand out through clear communication, solid references, attention to detail, and a
            strong track record of reliable work. When there's no license requirement, taking time to choose carefully
            protects your home and your investment.
          </p>
        </div>
      </header>

      <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="law-heading">
        <h2 id="law-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">What the Law Actually Says</h2>
        <p>
          The 2021 change came through House Bill 735, which classified painting as a specialty trade the state does not
          regulate. It also prohibited local governments from creating their own licensing rules for it. Senate Bill
          1142, effective July 1, 2025, closed the remaining gaps.
        </p>
        <p>
          As a result, painting is no longer a licensed trade at either the state or local level in Brevard County. This
          is clear statewide law, not a gray area.
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="watercolor-divider" aria-hidden="true"></div>

      <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="homeowners-heading">
        <h2 id="homeowners-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          What This Means for Homeowners
        </h2>
        <p>
          Licenses used to provide a basic level of screening. They required exams, insurance, and proof of financial
          responsibility. That filter no longer exists for painting.
        </p>
        <p>
          This doesn't mean quality painters have disappeared — plenty of good ones are still out there. It simply means
          the responsibility for choosing wisely now rests more fully with you as the homeowner.
        </p>
        <p>
          In Florida's challenging climate (high humidity, salt air, heavy rain, and intense sun), a poorly done paint
          job fails faster and costs more to fix later. That's why vetting matters more than ever.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-8" aria-labelledby="look-for-heading">
        <h2 id="look-for-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">What to Look for Instead</h2>
        <p>
          Since a painting license is no longer part of the picture, focus on these practical signs of a professional
          crew:
        </p>
        {
          vettingItems.map((item) => (
            <div class="space-y-3">
              <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold sm:text-2xl">{item.heading}</h3>
              <p>{item.body}</p>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </section>

      <section
        class="space-y-5 rounded-xl border border-purple/20 bg-purple/5 p-6 sm:p-8"
        aria-labelledby="homeowner-tips-heading"
      >
        <h2 id="homeowner-tips-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">Homeowner Tips</h2>
        <p>
          For a deeper walkthrough on hiring in Brevard County — questions to ask, what good prep looks like, and what to
          expect during your project — start with our{' '}
          <a
            href="/homeowner-guide"
            class="font-semibold text-purple transition-colors hover:text-coral"
          >
            Homeowner Guide
          </a>
          .
        </p>
        <p>
          Ready to talk about your home? Fill out the form on our{' '}
          <a href="/contact" class="font-semibold text-purple transition-colors hover:text-coral">contact page</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <nav class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="see-also-heading">
        <h2 id="see-also-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">See Also</h2>
        <ul class="space-y-3">
          <li>
            <a
              href="/homeowner-guide/hiring-a-painter-brevard-county"
              class="font-medium text-purple transition-colors hover:text-coral"
            >
              Hiring a Painter in Brevard County →
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="/homeowner-guide/questions-to-ask-before-you-hire"
              class="font-medium text-purple transition-colors hover:text-coral"
            >
              Questions to Ask Before You Hire →
            </a>
          </li>
          <li class="pt-2">
            <a href="/blog" class="font-medium text-muted transition-colors hover:text-charcoal">
              ← Back to the Blog
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </nav>
    </article>
  </main>
</Layout>
